  "prompt": "How does the fuel reserve in a car work?",
  "response": "The fuel reserve in a car works as follows:\n\n1. Fuel Tank Design\n- The fuel tank has a small additional volume below the normal fuel level\n- This reserve section ensures you can drive a short distance after the main fuel gauge reaches \"empty\"\n\n2. Fuel Gauge Indication\n- When the fuel gauge reaches \"E\" (empty), there's typically 1-2 gallons of fuel remaining\n- This reserve allows you to drive approximately 30-50 miles, depending on the vehicle\n\n3. Low Fuel Warning\n- Most modern cars have a low fuel warning light that illuminates when the fuel reaches reserve levels\n- This alerts the driver to refuel soon\n\n4. Mechanism\n- A float sensor in the fuel tank measures fuel level\n- When fuel drops below a certain point, it triggers the low fuel warning light\n- The reserve fuel is drawn through the same fuel line as the main tank\n\n5. Purpose\n- Prevents complete engine shutdown if fuel runs low\n- Gives drivers time to find a gas station\n- Protects fuel pump from damage by preventing it from running dry\n\n6. Variation\n- Reserve volume varies by vehicle make and model\n- Typically ranges from 1-2 gallons\n\nAlways recommended to refuel before reaching the reserve to maintain vehicle health and avoid potential fuel system issues.",
